'''Vincent Joseph Colletta''' ([[October 15]], [[1920s|1923]] &ndash; [[June 3]], [[1991]]) was a veteran artist for [[Marvel Comics]] who worked on dozens of projects as both a penciller and an embellisher, including one issue in the [[Star Wars (1977)|''Marvel Star Wars'']] comic series. Colletta is best known for his inking talents and for utilizing a distinctive heavy, line-style that made him a heavily sought-after talent in the field of comics.

Colletta began working in comics in [[1950s|1952]] as a penciller, mainly on romance titles, for several publishers including [[Wikipedia:Archie Comics|Archie Comics]], [[Wikipedia:Charlton Comics|Charlton Comics]], and [[Wikipedia:Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]]. In the 1960s he began working on superhero titles, focusing chiefly on inking, including the Marvel title [[Wikipedia:Daredevil (Marvel Comics)|''Daredevil'']]. It was around that time that he first collaborated with penciller [[Wikipedia:Jack Kirby|Jack Kirby]], and they worked on [[Wikipedia:Journey into Mystery|''Journey into Mystery'']] starring [[Wikipedia:Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] for six years.

When Kirby moved to [[Wikipedia:DC Comics|DC Comics]] in the 1970s, Colletta moved with him and the two continued to produce work together on several projects including [[Wikipedia:Jimmy Olsen|''Superman's Pal Jimmy Olsen'']] and [[Wikipedia:New Gods|''The New Gods'']]. He was also the regular inker for [[Wikipedia:Wonder Woman|''Wonder Woman'']] from [[1973]] to [[1980]]. In [[1976]] Colletta was named DC's art director, a title he held until [[1979]]. He continued to ink on a variety of projects for both Marvel and DC until the late 1980s.

